    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-11-17T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-11-17T17:00:00-05:00" n="956"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d956">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">852.48/782: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Weddell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Madrid</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-11-17T23:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 17, 1940—11 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 18—7:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>654. The Naval Attaché<note n="40" xml:id="d956fn40">Commander Ben H.
                        Wyatt.</note> informs me that he has just been told by the chief of the
                    Spanish Merchant Marine Shipping Board that he has been ordered by the Minister
                    of Industry and Commerce to hold in readiness one-half of his tramp tonnage or
                    approximately 350,000 tons of shipping to be sent to a destination to be
                    indicated later for the purpose of bringing wheat to Spain of a total tonnage of
                    450 tons which will be supplied by Germany.</p>
                <p>The British Chargé d’Affaires tells me that he has been informed that such an
                    offer has been made. However, I share the Naval Attaché’s entire skepticism as
                    to the feasibility of effective deliveries.</p>
                <p>The subject appears to be of interest as indicating the efforts which Germany is
                    now making to offset any offers of foodstuffs which might be made to Spain by
                    any other Governments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Weddell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
